{"cursor":"26310","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n'Insight' is the understanding of a specific cause and effect in a specific\ncontext. The term insight can have several related meanings: *a piece of\ninformation *the act or result of understanding the inner nature of things or of\nseeing intuitively in Greek called noesis *an introspection *the power of acute\nobservation and deduction, penetration, discernment, perception called\nintellection or noesis *an understanding of cause and effect based on\nidentification of relationships and behaviors within a model, context, or\nscenario (see artificial intelligence)\n\nAn insight that manifests itself suddenly, such as understanding how to solve a\ndifficult problem, is sometimes called by the German word [[Eureka effect|Aha-\nErlebnis]]. The term was coined by the German psychologist and theoretical\nlinguist Karl BÃ¼hler. It is also known as an epiphany.\n","linknr":399,"url":"Insight","recorded":1362540037,"links":28,"instances":["knowledge","feeling"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Epistemology","Sources of knowledge","Creativity","Social psychology"],"headings":["Psychology","Psychiatry","Religion","Marketing","See also","References","Further reading"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f8/Wiktionary-logo-en.svg/37px-Wiktionary-logo-en.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0b/Duncker_Candle_Problem%2C_DLW.png/220px-Duncker_Candle_Problem%2C_DLW.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/7/7f/Nine_Dot_Problem%2C_DLW.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/08/RAT_problem%2C_DLW.png/220px-RAT_problem%2C_DLW.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/a/a8/RAT_Problem%2C_DLW.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static